# A deceptive statement, especially one that is only partly true, is incomplete, is given out of context, uses a word with an atypical meaning, is a literal part of a truth,  or misrepresents reality.
--[[User:Caesarjbsquitti|Caesarjbsquitti]] 02:58, 13 August 2006 (UTC)

Example:

"Stop violence against women", contains two half-truths, and a third is implied.  1. Violence is merely one form of abuse, the real issue is abuse, not merely violence.  2.  The focus in on women, and the model ignores men and children.  3.  The model is usually exploited to presume that all violence against women is by men.

